Part I - Bike-sharing Data Exploration¶

by Oluyimika Sosanya¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset which containing duration and other attributes for approximately 2,410,000 individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area in 2019. The goal of my analysis is to answer the following questions:

  1. How long does the average trip take?
  2. Does average trip duration depend on user type?
  3. When are most trips taken in terms of time of day, day of the week, or month of the year?

# Loop through url list to download data programatically using Requests
for url in bikeShareUrls:
    response = requests.get(url)
    # Save datafile into the directory
    with open(os.path.join(filePath, url.split('/')[-1]), mode='wb') as file:
        file.write(response.content)
In [5]:
# Create a list to hold the full file directory of the downloaded Zip files
bikeShareZip = []
#Use for loop to extract file name from bikeShareUrls
for url in bikeShareUrls:
    zipFile = filePath + '/' + url.split('/')[-1]
    bikeShareZip.append(zipFile)
    
# Extract all the contents in the zip file into the working directory
for fileDir in bikeShareZip:
    with zipfile.ZipFile(fileDir, 'r') as myzip:
        myzip.extractall()

Observation:

rental_access_method column has the least number of non-null values. Data points for this column was only available for 4 (June, July, November & December) out of 12 months, and there were more null values for these months. Since missing values in this column are more than 90% of the entire observations in the dataset, I will drop it.

There are records for bike_share_for_all_trip in every month, except December. I also observed missing values in June, July and November only. Since there are no records for the month of December I'll keep these rows.

There are missing records for station ids and station names in 9 out of 12 months. The close number of missing records suggests a relationship: either they are test stations or makeshift stations. However, since these rows wouldn't be useful for my analysis, I will drop them and proceed with further wrangling.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 2,407,259 individual rides in the dataset with 14 features _(duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, bike_share_for_alltrip). Most variables are qualitative in nature but the variables duration_sec, latitudes, and longitudes are numeric, while start and end times are datetime.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the duration of bike rides in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that User Type would have the strongest effect on each ride duration: "registered" members have more ride time included in their plan than non-members. I also think that time_of_day, day_of_week, and month will have an effect on ride time but to a lesser degree.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I extended my investigation of duration_sec against user type in this section by looking at the impact of the period feature. The multivariate exploration here showed that indeed there is an effect of user type on ride duration. This was initially hidden in the dataset due to the fact that Subscribers, who had the largest share of trips, have individual rides that lasted for a short duration overall.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

While my exploration established that customers ride for a longer duration on average, it was interesting to observe the inverse relationship amonng user type between 9am and 2pm.

Also, Customers had bike rides for short duration, similar to that of subscribers, in December. This might be connected with an increased amount of time spent indoors due to the festivities in that period.

Conclusions¶

To make the dataset ready for exploration, it required that I performed some data wrangling. I gathered the dataset by downloading separated tables programmatically, I merged all into a master dataset for a full year coverage, assessed and then cleaned highlighted issues. Afterwards, I began exploratory analysis operations on the dataset and made the following findings:

  1. The duration of an average trip is strongly associated with if a user is a subscriber or a customer. Subscribers tend to take more trips with short durations of around 300 seconds with only few lasting for longer duration.
  2. Bike are a functional utility for Subscribers due to the consistent pattern seen in trip duration during working hours, work days, and months with more work days. The popular start and end stations were fairly consistent suggesting frequent trips between these stations.
  3. Most trips are taken during weekdays and in the hours leading to and following the official working hours. Bike rides were also slightly dependent on seasonal trends with most trips (and an increased duration) observed in the spring.

The exploration depicts that the bike scheme is a preffered means of commute for Subscribers who are mainly locals/residents of the greater San Francisco Bay Area.
